iltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oare, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gitton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>gitoun</i> ‘military or guild banner’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>guidon</i>), though the post-medieval bearers may belong to (2).","2  Welsh:  see  Gethin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gitting","meanings":["Welsh, English: variant of   Gethin   or   Gitton  .  Compare  Gitten  ."]},{"name":"Gethin","meanings":["(1997: 18;2007: 39; 2010: NA)","Welsh: from the personal name <i>Gethin</i>, perhaps a soft-mutated form of <i>cethin</i> ‘dusky, swarthy’."]},{"name":"Gethins","meanings":["1  Welsh, English, Scottish: (i) variant of   Gethin  , with English genitival or excrescent  <i>-s</i>. (ii) possibly also a variant of   Gitton   (1) with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>.","2  Irish: if not the Welsh name in Ireland, this name may have been adopted as a shortened form of  <b>Mag Eiteagáin</b>,  see  McGettigan  ."]},{"name":"Gitten","meanings":["Welsh, English: variant of   Gethin   or   Gitton  .  Compare  Gitting  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSu